`crates/ctx-summarize/src` is the leaf-up context-summarization pipeline: given source paths, it produces `.ctx` files per file and `rollup.ctx` per directory by driving an external LLM agent through prompt templates loaded at runtime. Depending on this crate as a library means calling `runner::run`/`run_with_prompts`; as a binary it's `ctx-summarize <paths>` with required `--leaf-model`/`--rollup-model`.

Layering is strict and one-directional: `cli` parses argv and calls `runner`; `runner` is pure orchestration that depends only on the `Fs` and `Agent` trait seams (`fs.rs`, `agent.rs`) plus `progress.rs` for status callbacks; `cpath` and `rollup_input` are internal helpers `runner` uses to compute `.context` mirror paths and assemble rollup prompts from children's `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files. `error.rs` defines the single `SummError` enum every fallible path returns — variant names/shapes are load-bearing for CLI exit-code mapping in `main.rs`.

Two safety gates span the subtree and must stay aligned: `fs::scope_matcher` (gitignore-syntax, `.ctxignore` + built-in `target/`) defines what's summarizable, checked via `Fs::is_ignored` and enforced in `runner::summarize_leaf` alongside `ctx_core::access`; and `runner::scope_check`/`cli::dispatch` enforce the `MAX_TARGETS` cost guard requiring `--approve`. Changing either gate's threshold or ignore rules needs checking against `ctx-scan`'s walker, which shares the same scope_matcher logic.

The `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` mirror-path convention lives once in `cpath.rs` (deliberately duplicated from `ctx-context`, tracked for later consolidation) and is used by both `runner` and `rollup_input` — any change to that layout must update both consumers. Agent calls are always synchronous request/response JSON over stdio (`agent.rs`), never inline, and `progress.rs` notifies just before each call. Prompts are always loaded from disk (`prompts/summarizer-leaf.md`, `summarizer-rollup.md`), never embedded in the binary.